00:12:38.527 --> 00:12:41.154
♪ Que tenga dinero ♪

247
00:12:41.238 --> 00:12:43.073
♪ Y que no se muera... ♪

248
00:12:43.156 --> 00:12:46.785
EDUARDO MACHADO:
<i>I remember the first time I saw Ricky.</i>


249
00:12:46.868 --> 00:12:50.497
I was a kid growing up
in the San Fernando Valley.


250
00:12:50.580 --> 00:12:52.791
-Good morning, dear.
<i>-And I kind of learned English</i>


251
00:12:52.874 --> 00:12:55.919
from watching <i>I Love Lucy,</i> you know.

252
00:12:56.002 --> 00:12:57.963
<i>-...a sus saludes.</i>
<i>-A la salud. -A cubita bella.</i>


253
00:12:58.046 --> 00:13:00.257
Uh, <i>l'chaim.</i>

254
00:13:00.340 --> 00:13:01.633
(audience laughter)

255
00:13:01.716 --> 00:13:04.219
MACHADO:
<i>Desi brought sophistication</i>


256
00:13:04.302 --> 00:13:09.432
<i>where Latinos have hardly ever</i>
<i>been seen as sophisticated.</i>


257
00:13:09.516 --> 00:13:11.184
♪ Babalú... ♪

258
00:13:11.268 --> 00:13:12.519
(shouts)

259
00:13:12.602 --> 00:13:14.854
MACHADO:
<i>There was Carmen Miranda.</i>


260
00:13:14.938 --> 00:13:16.189
<i>She had bananas.</i>

261
00:13:16.273 --> 00:13:20.485
<i>There were Cesar Romero,</i>
<i>but he didn't play Cuban.</i>


262
00:13:20.569 --> 00:13:24.114
<i>And Desi came in and said,</i>
<i>"I'm Cuban Pete.</i>


263
00:13:24.197 --> 00:13:25.657
<i>I'm the king of the rumba beat."</i>

264
00:13:25.740 --> 00:13:27.701
♪ Olé, olé, olé, olé ♪

265
00:13:27.784 --> 00:13:31.162
-♪<i>Olé, olé, olé, olé</i>♪
-♪ Olé, olé, olé, olé ♪


266
00:13:31.246 --> 00:13:32.747
♪ <i>Olé, olé, olé, olé</i>♪

267
00:13:40.213 --> 00:13:41.423
Ah!

268
00:13:42.424 --> 00:13:44.092
Yeah!

269
00:13:44.175 --> 00:13:45.427
Ah!

270
00:13:45.510 --> 00:13:47.220
(band playing flourish)

271
00:13:47.304 --> 00:13:51.224
Ah! Yeah! Yeah! Ah!

272
00:13:52.767 --> 00:13:53.852
-Hey!
-(song ends)


273
00:13:53.935 --> 00:13:56.646
(seagulls chirping)

274
00:13:56.730 --> 00:14:00.150
(ship horn blows)

275
00:14:00.233 --> 00:14:02.944
DESI:
<i>I got to this country, you know, broke,</i>


276
00:14:03.028 --> 00:14:05.947
<i>and, uh, I didn't speak the language.</i>

277
00:14:06.031 --> 00:14:09.159
<i>So... I was just
trying to make a dollar.</i>

278
00:14:09.242 --> 00:14:11.077
<i>(laughs)</i>

279
00:14:11.161 --> 00:14:13.246
<i>'Cause I had nothing to start out with.</i>

280
00:14:13.330 --> 00:14:15.248
♪ ♪

281
00:14:15.332 --> 00:14:17.375
<i>Well, my father said, "Today you're 16.</i>

282
00:14:17.459 --> 00:14:20.670
<i>"In my book, that means</i>
<i>that you're no longer a child.</i>


283
00:14:20.754 --> 00:14:22.088
<i>You're now a man."</i>

284
00:14:24.132 --> 00:14:28.053
<i>This fellow was raising canaries,</i>
<i>and my job was to clean the cages.</i>


285
00:14:28.136 --> 00:14:30.972
<i>I got $15 a week and one meal.</i>

286
00:14:31.056 --> 00:14:35.060
<i>Some guy had a little band</i>
<i>called the Siboney Septet.</i>


287
00:14:35.143 --> 00:14:37.771
<i>He offered me $39 a week.</i>

288
00:14:37.854 --> 00:14:40.273
<i>So that's how I got into show business.</i>

289
00:14:40.357 --> 00:14:43.109
("Bésame" by Mongo Santamaria
playing, lyrics in Spanish)


290
00:14:44.819 --> 00:14:46.655
LUCIE:
<i>My father finished high school</i>


291
00:14:46.738 --> 00:14:48.698
<i>by the skin of his teeth,</i>

292
00:14:48.782 --> 00:14:53.286
<i>but he got an opportunity</i>
<i>to learn from the best.</i>


293
00:14:53.370 --> 00:14:55.288
<i>My father always said</i>
<i>he learned everything he knew</i>


294
00:14:55.372 --> 00:14:58.083
<i>about the band business</i>
<i>from working with Xavier Cugat.</i>


295
00:14:59.000 --> 00:15:01.795
CHARO:
<i>He was the king of the rhumba.</i>


296
00:15:01.878 --> 00:15:04.589
<i>The king of Latin music.</i>

297
00:15:04.964 --> 00:15:07.592
Now he saw me when
I was 16 years old.

298
00:15:08.009 --> 00:15:11.554
<i>And that's how I ended up</i>
<i>in the United States of America.</i>


299
00:15:11.638 --> 00:15:13.181
And people liked me. Thank God!

300
00:15:14.265 --> 00:15:18.228
<i>Cugat discovered a lot</i>
<i>of excellent talented people,</i>


301
00:15:18.311 --> 00:15:20.563
<i>and I am one of them.</i>

302
00:15:21.940 --> 00:15:23.900
(trilling)

303
00:15:23.983 --> 00:15:26.236
(whooping rhythmically)

304
00:15:26.319 --> 00:15:28.113
<i>Cugat discovered Desi.</i>

305
00:15:28.196 --> 00:15:30.740
<i>And he could see</i>
<i>that he was a real dreamer.</i>


306
00:15:30.824 --> 00:15:32.826
(singing in Spanish)

307
00:15:35.829 --> 00:15:38.873
<i>I met Desi because I knew Xavier Cugat.</i>

308
00:15:38.957 --> 00:15:40.291
They have a lot in common,

309
00:15:40.375 --> 00:15:41.793
although Cugat was older.

310
00:15:42.252 --> 00:15:45.004
<i>Because Cugat grew up also in Cuba.</i>

311
00:15:45.088 --> 00:15:48.299
<i>So they were, like they say in America,</i>
<i>two peas in a pod.</i>


312
00:15:48.383 --> 00:15:52.011
<i>Cugat the maestro, and the student Desi.</i>

313
00:15:52.095 --> 00:15:54.139
(singing continues in Spanish)

314
00:15:55.849 --> 00:15:58.184
DESI: <i>It was the greatest</i>
<i>experience in the world.</i>


315
00:15:58.268 --> 00:16:00.895
<i>And even though he didn't pay much money,</i>

316
00:16:00.979 --> 00:16:03.440
<i>I learned a hell of a lot</i>
<i>about the band business.</i>


317
00:16:03.523 --> 00:16:05.734
<i>Was like going to college.</i>

318
00:16:08.737 --> 00:16:10.989
(song ends)

319
00:16:11.072 --> 00:16:14.367
LUCY (over speakers):
I was so grateful to be any part


320
00:16:14.451 --> 00:16:16.202
of the business.

321
00:16:16.286 --> 00:16:17.454
(helicopter whirring)

322
00:16:17.537 --> 00:16:18.663
<i>I was a part of it.</i>

323
00:16:18.747 --> 00:16:19.956
<i>I didn't care what I did.</i>

324
00:16:20.039 --> 00:16:23.293
<i>They never had to ask me twice</i>
<i>to do anything.</i>


325
00:16:23.376 --> 00:16:25.003
♪ ♪

326
00:16:27.046 --> 00:16:28.965
<i>I said, "I want to know about this.</i>

327
00:16:29.048 --> 00:16:31.634
<i>I want to know how to do this."</i>

328
00:16:33.511 --> 00:16:35.638
<i>In those days,</i>
<i>there were no working hours.</i>


329
00:16:35.722 --> 00:16:37.265
<i>We worked all day and all night,</i>

330
00:16:37.348 --> 00:16:38.808
<i>maybe 3:00 in the morning.</i>

331
00:16:38.892 --> 00:16:41.019
<i>And we'd be there at 6:00.</i>

332
00:16:42.896 --> 00:16:46.524
<i>See, when you're not beautiful</i>
<i>and you're not too bright,</i>


333
00:16:46.608 --> 00:16:49.569
<i>you attract attention any way you can.</i>

334
00:16:49.652 --> 00:16:51.863
The trouble with you is
you're all trying to be comics.


335
00:16:51.946 --> 00:16:53.740
Don't you ever take anything seriously?

336
00:16:53.823 --> 00:16:55.909
After you've sat around for a year
trying to get a job,


337
00:16:55.992 --> 00:16:57.452
you won't take anything seriously either.

338
00:16:57.535 --> 00:17:00.413
LUCY:
<i>So I got a chance to work many times</i>


339
00:17:00.497 --> 00:17:02.415
<i>because I didn't mind what I did.</i>

340
00:17:02.499 --> 00:17:04.042
<i>I just knew it was action.</i>

341
00:17:04.125 --> 00:17:06.961
<i>It was just doing something</i>
<i>that no one else wanted to do.</i>


342
00:17:10.715 --> 00:17:13.885
<i>Those were the days when you had</i>
<i>a mom-and-a-pop, uh, studio.</i>


343
00:17:13.968 --> 00:17:16.137
♪ ♪

344
00:17:17.722 --> 00:17:20.183
<i>They were our security.</i>

345
00:17:20.266 --> 00:17:24.479
<i>They had publicity departments</i>
<i>who made us a certain type.</i>


346
00:17:24.562 --> 00:17:26.356
<i>They dressed us, they trained us.</i>

347
00:17:26.439 --> 00:17:29.776
<i>They shoved us into "B" pictures</i>
<i>whether we wanted it or not.</i>


348
00:17:29.859 --> 00:17:31.778
<i>I never minded it.</i>

349
00:17:31.861 --> 00:17:34.197
<i>I knew I was getting</i>
<i>a well-paid apprenticeship.</i>


350
00:17:34.280 --> 00:17:35.490
<i>That's the difference.</i>

351
00:17:36.699 --> 00:17:39.953
<i>Lela was the first one at RKO</i>
<i>who was giving any thought</i>


352
00:17:40.036 --> 00:17:42.121
<i>to the young people</i>
<i>that were under contract there.</i>


353
00:17:42.205 --> 00:17:45.834
<i>And I became, by her own admission,</i>
<i>one of her best students.</i>


354
00:17:45.917 --> 00:17:47.502
<i>I was happily part of her group</i>

355
00:17:47.585 --> 00:17:49.254
<i>that she surrounded Ginger with</i>
<i>at the time.</i>


356
00:17:52.507 --> 00:17:54.676
<i>Ginger worked harder than</i>

357
00:17:54.759 --> 00:17:56.761
<i>anybody I've ever known in the business.</i>

358
00:17:56.845 --> 00:18:00.098
<i>Ginger was not, uh,</i>
<i>a great dancer when she started.</i>


359
00:18:00.181 --> 00:18:02.100
<i>-She was not a big star.</i>
-(camera clicking)


360
00:18:02.183 --> 00:18:03.726
<i>She was not a great actress.</i>

361
00:18:03.810 --> 00:18:05.603
<i>She learned all these things,</i>

362
00:18:05.687 --> 00:18:08.815
<i>and she learned it with real hard work.</i>

363
00:18:11.609 --> 00:18:13.152
<i>RKO was very good to me.</i>

364
00:18:13.236 --> 00:18:15.196
<i>And it was just, uh, a place</i>

365
00:18:15.280 --> 00:18:18.533
<i>that I was very grateful</i>
<i>to have grown up in.</i>


366
00:18:18.616 --> 00:18:20.702
<i>Eventually, they would</i>
<i>send me scripts and say,</i>


367
00:18:20.785 --> 00:18:22.412
<i>"Would you like to do this?"</i>

368
00:18:22.495 --> 00:18:26.708
<i>One day, I saw on a script</i>
<i>"Lucille Ball type."</i>


369
00:18:26.791 --> 00:18:29.252
<i>That was one of</i>
<i>the biggest thrills I had ever...</i>


370
00:18:29.335 --> 00:18:30.879
<i>uh, could imagine.</i>

371
00:18:30.962 --> 00:18:34.465
<i>Imagine anybody knew who Lucille Ball was.</i>

372
00:18:43.099 --> 00:18:44.642
DESI:
<i>I said, "Cugat, I got to quit.</i>


373
00:18:44.726 --> 00:18:46.603
<i>I got to get my little band."</i>

374
00:18:46.686 --> 00:18:49.772
<i>He says, "Go to Miami,"</i>
<i>so I got a little job down there.</i>


375
00:18:49.856 --> 00:18:52.358
<i>I says, "I got the job. 
Send me the band."</i>

376
00:18:52.442 --> 00:18:53.818
(band playing jazzy Cuban music)

377
00:18:53.902 --> 00:18:56.487
<i>We played the first set,</i>
<i>the guy says, "You're fired."</i>


378
00:18:56.571 --> 00:18:58.364
<i>(laughter)</i>

379
00:18:58.448 --> 00:19:02.243
<i>He says, "That is the worst sound</i>
<i>I have ever heard in my life."</i>


380
00:19:02.327 --> 00:19:04.037
<i>(laughter)</i>

381
00:19:04.120 --> 00:19:05.830
<i>And he was right.</i>

382
00:19:07.206 --> 00:19:09.292
<i>So I said, "Let
me try to figure out."</i>

383
00:19:09.375 --> 00:19:11.419
<i>And I had this
big conga drum with me.</i>

384
00:19:11.502 --> 00:19:15.173
<i>Now, in Cuba, everybody does</i>
<i>the conga in Carnival time,</i>


385
00:19:15.256 --> 00:19:16.925
<i>particularly in my hometown.</i>

386
00:19:17.008 --> 00:19:18.927
<i>It's like the Mardi Gras in New Orleans.</i>

387
00:19:19.010 --> 00:19:21.763
<i>Everybody from the island</i>
<i>comes to Santiago,</i>


388
00:19:21.846 --> 00:19:23.348
<i>and they do the conga line.</i>

389
00:19:23.431 --> 00:19:24.557
(music ends)

390
00:19:24.641 --> 00:19:25.934
<i>I bought a bottle of rum.</i>

391
00:19:26.017 --> 00:19:28.603
<i>I says, "Drink up. We're gonna</i>
<i>play something new."</i>


392
00:19:28.686 --> 00:19:30.688
(band playing lively conga music)

393
00:19:35.401 --> 00:19:37.862
<i>-That's how the conga started.</i>
<i>-(man laughing)</i>


394
00:19:37.946 --> 00:19:39.948
<i>My dance of desperation.</i>

395
00:19:41.074 --> 00:19:44.243
MACHADO: <i>All those rhythms,</i>
<i>they were all Afro-Cuban.</i>


396
00:19:44.327 --> 00:19:49.707
And he took that and made it
the definition of Cuba for the world.


397
00:19:49.791 --> 00:19:52.335
JUDY GARLAND:
♪ One, two, three ♪


398
00:19:52.418 --> 00:19:53.670
♪ Boom! ♪

399
00:20:01.177 --> 00:20:02.845
CHARO:
<i>1... 2... 3... Kick!</i>


400
00:20:03.096 --> 00:20:04.889
<i>1... 2... 3... Kick!</i>

401
00:20:04.973 --> 00:20:07.517
When you have that rhythm so heavy,

402
00:20:07.600 --> 00:20:10.561
all percussion. 
It goes to your bones.

403
00:20:12.605 --> 00:20:15.984
DESI: <i>I did a play on Broadway</i>
<i>called</i>Too Many Girls.


404
00:20:16.067 --> 00:20:19.362
<i>And then RKO bought it for a film,</i>

405
00:20:19.445 --> 00:20:23.157
<i>and they brought me out to Hollywood</i>
<i>to do my part I did on Broadway.</i>


406
00:20:23.241 --> 00:20:24.659
-(performers cheering)
-(lively music playing)


407
00:20:28.997 --> 00:20:30.456
LUCY:
<i>I was told that I was</i>


408
00:20:30.540 --> 00:20:33.751
<i>going to play an ingenue</i>
<i>in</i>Too Many Girls.


409
00:20:33.835 --> 00:20:36.212
<i>And, uh, at that time,</i>

410
00:20:36.295 --> 00:20:38.256
<i>I did a picture called</i>Dance, Girl, Dance,

411
00:20:38.339 --> 00:20:41.009
<i>which was a real brassy burlesque queen.</i>

412
00:20:41.092 --> 00:20:42.635
(crowd jeering)

413
00:20:43.845 --> 00:20:45.304
(crowd gasping, murmuring)

414
00:20:46.639 --> 00:20:48.641
(women screaming)

415
00:20:48.725 --> 00:20:50.643
<i>I had been doing that scene all day,</i>

416
00:20:50.727 --> 00:20:53.938
<i>and so I went at lunchtime</i>
<i>into the commissary.</i>


417
00:20:54.022 --> 00:20:57.608
<i>I had a big black eye</i>
<i>and bruises on my face.</i>


418
00:20:57.692 --> 00:21:01.362
<i>And in that interim, 
I met Desi Arnaz.</i>

419
00:21:01.446 --> 00:21:03.072
DESI:
<i>We were rehearsing the music,</i>


420
00:21:03.156 --> 00:21:04.949
<i>directed by George Abbott.</i>

421
00:21:05.033 --> 00:21:08.953
<i>I said to Mr. Abbott,</i>
<i>"She's gonna be the ingenue?</i>


422
00:21:09.037 --> 00:21:10.288
<i>You're out of your mind."</i>

423
00:21:10.371 --> 00:21:12.290
♪ ♪

424
00:21:15.043 --> 00:21:18.463
DESI: <i>Later on that afternoon,</i>
<i>it was the first get-together,</i>


425
00:21:18.546 --> 00:21:21.007
<i>and I said to
the piano player, I said,</i>

426
00:21:21.090 --> 00:21:23.509
<i>"Oh, my, that's a hunk of woman."</i>

427
00:21:27.638 --> 00:21:29.557
<i>He says, "You met her this morning.</i>

428
00:21:29.640 --> 00:21:31.392
